This paper deals with the construction of a finite recognizer for hairpin completions of regular languages, which is a topic related to formal languages and automata theory. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.FL (Formal Languages and Automata Theory). The paper also involves the use of derivation techniques, which are related to computational complexity and algorithms, making cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) another likely category. The paper also discusses the linear context-free property of hairpin completions, which is related to logic and computation, making cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science) a possible category. Additionally, the paper involves the design of a polynomial construction, which is related to programming languages and compilers, making cs.PL (Programming Languages) another possible category. Finally, the paper involves the use of automata theory and formal languages, which are related to theoretical computer science, making cs.SC (Symbolic Computation) a possible category.
